OUTER VIEW I used data on the federal prison population from 2005 thru 2017; There has been a sharp decrease in recent years, from fewer incarcerations during the Obama years and I wanted to better capture the trend using more recent data . Current population is 184,422 (12/7/17), trending downward but is expected to increase. The 2018 estimate was formed using time series analysis (TS) and simple regression. 190,023 | Regression . Population regressed on year 196, 782 | Exponential TS 200, 482 | Average change over the period. 198,946 | Moving average using two previous years to forecast following year. INSIDE VIEW From the Wall Street Journal Article (6/8/17, Beth Reinhard) , Trump promises to step up prosecutions for drug offenses and illegal immigrants. Jeff Sessions, attorney general, has scuttled the Obama administration policy that avoids mandatory minimum penalties for non-violent offenders and has instructed federal prosecutors to charge for the "most seriously readily provable offense". Militating again this initiative are the need for prison reform and improved infrastructure (Money) . Fewer clemency grants are expected than Obama's 1,927 (most since Truman). The WSJ article estimates the population as 4,171 (2%) to 191,493. Estimates are shown above.

Fears come in two flavours--unfounded and reasonable. Almost all stupid policies come from the former, and the Attorney General has adopted one. However, it takes a while for changes in sentencing pratices to work their way into the prison system. First, some trials are already going on or are about to wrap up under arrangements made during the grownup period. These may not add as heavily to inmate population as later ones will. Also in this category are the ones which have ended but see a fairly long stretch of time between conviction and sentencing. Second, there are appeals, which take a while and mayn't add much to inmate populations if their subjects are out on bail or retained in state or local joints in the interim. Third, many district and appellate judges were Obama appointments and unless they are confronted with mandatory sentencing, may opt to keep people out of the slammer, and that's before you get to bench trials in which Obama judges may find a defendant Not Guilty rather than BoP fodder. Fourth, many states' jury pools consist mostly of adults who will acquit low-level offenders rather than send them off to the tender mercies of Jeff Sessions. So while this stupid policy will undoubtedly increase BoP populations over the medium term (at your expense and mine and to no other actual effect, by the way), the big BoP population explosion may not hit until second or third Q of '18.

Given the dysfunction of the U.S. court system and the overwhelming pressure placed on public defenders at all levels (https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/sep/07/public-defender-us-criminal-justice-system), coupled with antiquated drug laws and a resurgence under AG Sessions of increased punishment for drug crimes (http://www.courier-journal.com/story/opinion/contributors/2017/07/17/sessions-plan-harsher-penalties-wont-solve-drug-problem-richard-j-pocker/483161001/), makes it probable that the federal prison population will increase. Couple that with low likelihood of Trump granting pardons or clemency, especially at the levels of Obama during his last 3 years in office (https://www.justice.gov/pardon/clemency-statistics#obama), and an increased federal prison population seems more likely.

Having long ago learned the futility of seeking clarification in such instances, I shall go with an estimate of "total federal inmate," the big BoP number, assuming on the basis of no evidence that this was the Q's intent.

This is an interesting question. Looking at Bureau of Prison statistics, there were 187,489 federal inmates as of July 13, 2017 (https://www.bop.gov/about/statistics/population_statistics.jsp). Using the raw data, the federal prison population increased by 65K during Clinton's two terms, and 56K during Bush's two terms, both during a time of increased law enforcement and prison privatization. During Obama's two terms, the population decreased overall by just over 9K, after increasing by approximately 18K for the first 5 years before decreasing by approximately 26K in the last 3.
